    pearls: ["Waterhouse-Friderichsen syndrome = fulminant meningococcemia + bilateral adrenal hemorrhagic necrosis + DIC + shock — mortality exceeds 50% even with treatment","The adrenal glands are uniquely vulnerable to hemorrhage: three arteries supply each gland but only one vein drains it, creating a vascular bottleneck that promotes venous congestion during stress","Think adrenal hemorrhage in any anticoagulated patient with unexplained abdominal/flank pain + hemodynamic instability — especially if on heparin (HIT-related thrombosis)","Hypotension refractory to vasopressors is a key clinical clue — cortisol is required for catecholamine receptor sensitivity; vasopressors cannot work without adequate cortisol","Random cortisol levels in ICU patients must be interpreted in context: a 'normal' cortisol of 12 mcg/dL is inappropriately low for a critically ill patient in shock (expected >25-30 mcg/dL)"],
